<br>
There were two banzai trees on either side of the room in Derek's apartment. There was also a hanging tropical plant or something that engulfed the whole ceiling. The growing lights came on to give them their daily doseage of sunlight, and the blacklight-lit room brightened immensely. It was mostly blue light in the spectrum, enhancing the growth of leaves. All of a sudden, Derek could see blue. Everything was blue. The image shifted to green, and the room blotted out. There was no Mika. There was no Nefer. There was no Jash. There was no Carmen. There was no vid screen. There was no automated kitchen. But there were rocks. There were plants. There were trees, and birds, and air, and a stream, and cliffs, and dropoffs, and mountains...<br>
<br>
Derek was flying.<br>
<br>
Soaring out across the landscape, he realized this was the world as pure. Purity, before the obscene corruption. No, wait... this was after it. There were ruins of cities. Great, majestic birds flew from the tops, catching the thermals above massive lava beds. This was a tropical area. Open lava vents, mountains... for some reason, the word &quot;Andes&quot; popped into his head. South America, eh...?<br>
<br>
He was on the ground. Visions of spiders flashed through his eyes. Flash. Flash, flash. Tarantula. Black Widdow. Brown Lecluse. Spider, spider, SPIDERS!<br>
<br>
The spiders stopped. From the blackness of nothing emerged a sillhouetted shape. Derek shouted, &quot;ILLUMINAAAATE!&quot;  The darkness scattered away like scared puppies. Stalking forward, as if held up by a string, was a woman with a human torso and the body of a spider... much like Tsabo Tavoc, yet... not mutilated. &quot;Sp-e-eea-k,&quot; she whispered. Her unearthly voice seemed to leave ripples along his soul...<br>
<br>
She held out her hand. One leg almost glowed white. &quot;S-s-s-s-aa-rah,&quot;<br>
<br>
The legs stuttered and twitched. Each one seemed healthy, curled underneath her frame and drooping downwards. One leg had a yellowish tint to it. It seemed to cringe away from the fuzzy, black abdomen.<br>
<br>
She smiled. Derek looked down, and saw the second to front leg on her left side; it was shaking madly, twitching as if it wanted to be separated from its body. It was red... glowing red... Third from the front, on the right side, the blueish one, was still, calm. It didn't pulse, it didn't move... yet the blue tint began creeping over the red leg. She licked her lips. &quot;Mi-i-i-ka-&quot;<br>
<br>
The world flung backwards. Derek flew back away from everything, away from the forests, away from the landscape, and back into the room with a scream. His eyes were wide, tears streaming down his face. He was clutching the pillows and stuffing on the couch, the one he never allows harm to come to, and was ripping it apart with arms and feet spread wide.<br>
<br>
Even through their own weaknesses and distresses, Mika and Nefer ran to his side. Carmen bolted up, and Jash put his hand on his brother's shoulder ((figuratively speaking)). In a matter of seconds, Derek calmed down, bewildered. He embraced Mika, and kissed her fervently on the cheek. &quot;Don't let go, Mika. Keep a hold on it, don't EVER let go!&quot;<br>
<br>
For the first time, he remembered the beaten and battered Lor. Lor... &quot;Sarah, he says...&quot; Derek mumbled.<br>
<br>
Nefer's eyebrow went up. &quot;What did you say?&quot;<br>
<br>
Derek looked at her with an intense gaze. &quot;Sarah. This...&quot; Hairs stood on the back of his neck. Derek whipped around, and pushed through his friends to the wall. Yelling in rage, he brought his fist down on the wall, leaving a splattery mess where a spider once was. He grabbed a leather coat, neglecting the need for longer pants (( hell, shants are long enough )), and put the faltering Mika's arm around his shoulder. Nefer took the other. &quot;Sarah @#%$ Lor. Sarah's fuckin Mika. Sarah's gonna @#%$ us all. I say we @#%$ her first.&quot; As they made their way to the door, Derek tried to keep the thought out of his mind that he had no idea where they were headed... &quot;Computer! When Jerron and Devin get back, tell them to call my cellcom. We need to do this. Fast.&quot;<br>
<br>
They stepped out the door, Derek muttering about the cost of plane tickets to Peru...<br>
<br>
